{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:26:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:26:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12458"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12458"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.03,0.1,0.52,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4966"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24931"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1956"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-month-old infant is brought to the emergency department by her father with a six day history of lethargy, difficulty breathing, and swelling in her legs. She had previously been well, apart from a single episode of a respiratory tract infection when she was two months old.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 72/34 mmHg, pulse 128/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. She appears unwell but is not cyanosed. Her heart sounds are dual with a pansystolic murmur heard best in the left lower sternal border. Her abdomen is distended, but there is no thrill present. Her legs have pitting oedema up to the knees.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eisenmenger syndrome","Pericarditis","Infective endocarditis","Congestive heart Failure","Coarctation of aorta"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure, secondary to a ventricular septal defect (VSD) \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most likely diagnosis in this case. Her dyspnoea, oedema and ascites is consistent with decompensated heart failure, and her heart murmur characteristics are consistent with a VSD. The age and rapidity of onset of heart failure would vary with the size of the defect. Heart failure would occur within 1 - 3 months in those with large VSDs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEisenmenger syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eleads to cyanosis, desaturation, dyspnoea, syncope, and clubbing. Eisenmenger syndrome is a complication of congenital heart disease that occurs due to the reversal of a left-to-right shunt into a right-to-left shunt. It typically develops over a longer period of time (years to decades) and is much less common in infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoarctation of the aorta\u003C/strong\u003E is a narrowing of the aorta, which can cause headaches and leg cramps. The absence of a thrill in this case suggests that there is no significant obstruction of blood flow, making coarctation of the aorta less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfective endocarditis \u003C/strong\u003Eis an infection of the heart valves, which can cause fever, fatigue/lethargy, irritability, and decompensated heart failure. Joint pain can be present in older children and adults with endocarditis, but it is less likely to be present in infants. The manifestations of IE are non-specific and can be confused with other more common systemic infections, such as pneumonia or urinary tract infections. Tachycardia, feeding refusal, vomiting, or high fever are common. Seizures may appear as evidence of central nervous system involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammation of the pericardium, the sac surrounding the heart. Symptoms can include chest pain, fever, and difficulty breathing. While some of the symptoms of pericarditis overlap with the symptoms seen in this case, such as difficulty breathing, the presence of a pan systolic murmur and signs of heart failure make pericarditis much less likely. Auscultation classically reveals a left para sternal pericardial friction rub; which consists of a rasping, scratchy triphasic sound.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Congestive heart failure is the most likely complication of ventricular septal defect in an infant."],"references":["Dakkak W, Oliver TI. Ventricular Septal Defect. [Updated 2022 May 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Dababneh E, Siddique MS. Pericarditis. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Malik A, Brito D, Vaqar S, et al. Congestive Heart Failure. [Updated 2022 Nov 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24931"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12458"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24931"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-03T10:08:0